### Explanation
The proof uses the monotonicity of the integral operator to compare the integrals of `|∫ g'' s|` and `∫ |g'' s|`. Specifically:
1. For each `t ∈ [0,1]`, we have `|∫ (s : ℝ) in 0..t, g'' s| ≤ ∫ (s : ℝ) in 0..t, |g'' s|` (by `abs_int_le_int_abs`).
2. The functions `t ↦ |∫ (s : ℝ) in 0..t, g'' s|` and `t ↦ ∫ (s : ℝ) in 0..t, |g'' s|` are continuous (hence interval integrable) on `[0,1]`.
3. Using the monotonicity of integration, we deduce that the integral of the left-hand side is less than or equal to the integral of the right-hand side over `[0,1]`. 

The Lean proof leverages these facts to conclude that `∫ (t : ℝ) in 0..1, |∫ (s : ℝ) in 0..t, g'' s| ≤ ∫ (t : ℝ) in 0..1, ∫ (s : ℝ) in 0..t, |g'' s|`.

